That early return is meant to prevent removing the leading empty line in this edge case:

https://github.com/mvdan/gofumpt/blob/f2d9f32be31becb2f4d626dc07f83ca26268eb7f/testdata/scripts/func-newlines.txt#L50-L55

That is, if you end up with:

```
func multilineResults() (p1 string,
	p2 string) {
	println("body")
}
```

That's not good, because the parameter list and body aren't clearly separated. This is not a problem if the `) {` is on its own separate line, like in this thread:


```
func multilineResults() (p1 string,
	p2 string,
) {
	println("body")
}
```

The logic to do the early return should be adjusted to take this into account.

@nathan-415 if I add a `panic("hello")` right above that return line, `TestScripts/func-newlines` fails for me.

Another way to think about it is that, if I just remove the return line, then the test fails because those empty lines I mentioned above are removed by gofumpt:

```
            > cmp foo.go foo.go.golden
            --- foo.go
            +++ foo.go.golden
            @@ -21,6 +21,7 @@
             
             func multilineParams(p1 string,
             	p2 string) {
            +
             	println("body")
             }
             
            @@ -32,6 +33,7 @@
             
             func multilineResults() (p1 string,
             	p2 string) {
            +
             	println("body")
             }
             
            
            FAIL: testdata/scripts/func-newlines.txt:2: foo.go and foo.go.golden differ
```
